\par\pard\plain \tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\sa480\sl216\slmult1\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs36\b0\i0\cf5 About This Template<!$Scr_Ps::1>}
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\sa80\ltrch\loch {\f3\fs24\b0\i0 When compiled (}{\f4\fs20\b1\i0\cf6 <$Scr_Cs::2>File > Compile\loch\af4\hich\af4\dbch\af4\uc1\u8230\'85<!$Scr_Cs::2>}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 ), this project will generate a script in the BBC\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8217\'92s standard \u8220\'93scene style\u8221\'94 format for radio. Please see the \u8220\'93BBC Radio Format: Scene Style\u8221\'94 specifications for a description of the expected format, which you can find on the BBC Writers\u8217\'92 Room website here:}
\par\plain \f3\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/writersroom/scripts/bbcradioscene.pdf"}{\fldrslt\f3\fs24\b0\i0 http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/writersroom/scripts/bbcradioscene.pdf}}
\par\pard\plain \tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\sa60\sb560\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs34\b0\i0\cf7 <$Scr_Ps::3>How To Use This Template<!$Scr_Ps::3>}
\par\pard\plain \tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-360\sa80\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9642 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 Edit the \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93Title Page\u8221\'94 document in the \u8220\'93Front Matter\u8221\'94 folder to ensure it contains the correct information.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9642 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 Create a new text document for each scene inside the \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93Act\u8221\'94 folder.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1100\tx1440\li1440\fi-360\sa80\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl1{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9702 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 One way of doing this is to choose }{\f4\fs20\b1\i0\cf6 <$Scr_Cs::2>Project > New From Template > New Scene<!$Scr_Cs::2>}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (which is also available from the binder\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8217\'92s right-click contextual menu).}
\par\plain \ilvl1{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9702 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 Alternatively, click on the dropdown arrow beside the green \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93Add\u8221\'94 button in the toolbar and select \u8220\'93New Scene\u8221\'94 from the choice of document types.}
\par\plain \ilvl1{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9702 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 Finally, you can simply hit \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93Add\u8221\'94 or }{\f4\fs20\b1\i0\cf6 <$Scr_Cs::2>Ctrl+N<!$Scr_Cs::2>}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  while in the \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93Act\u8221\'94 folder to automatically create a \u8220\'93New Scene\u8221\'94 document (instead of a blank text document). This is because the \u8220\'93Act\u8221\'94 folder is set to use the \u8220\'93New Scene\u8221\'94 template as its default document type. This has been set via }{\f4\fs20\b1\i0\cf6 <$Scr_Cs::2>Documents > Default Template for Subdocuments<!$Scr_Cs::2>}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 .}
\par\plain \ilvl1{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9702 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 Any of the above methods will create a scene that already has the scene heading entered for you. (Note that the \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93<$N>\u8221\'94 in the scene headings will be changed to sequential numbers upon compile.)}
\par\plain \ilvl1{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9702 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 The template for the \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93New Scene\u8221\'94 document is contained in the \u8220\'93Templates\u8221\'94 folder (documents in that folder can be used as the basis for new documents and appear in the }{\f4\fs20\b1\i0\cf6 <$Scr_Cs::2>New From Template<!$Scr_Cs::2>}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  menu).}
\par\pard\plain \tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-360\sa80\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9642 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 You can create more \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93Act\u8221\'94 folders if you wish, although this is not necessary. (A page break will be inserted between acts on Compile.) To do so, go to }{\f4\fs20\b1\i0\cf6 <$Scr_Cs::2>Project > New From Template > New Act<!$Scr_Cs::2>}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 . Doing this rather than just adding a regular folder will ensure that new documents added to your act folder will be of the \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93New Scene\u8221\'94 type rather than blank text documents. This is because the \u8220\'93New Act\u8221\'94 template folder has been set to use the \u8220\'93New Scene\u8221\'94 template as its default document type (via }{\f4\fs20\b1\i0\cf6 <$Scr_Cs::2>Documents > Default Template for Subdocuments<!$Scr_Cs::2>}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 ).}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9642 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 Ensure you are in script mode (}{\f4\fs20\b1\i0\cf6 <$Scr_Cs::2>Format > Scriptwriting > Script Mode<!$Scr_Cs::2>}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 ) when typing your scenes (when in script mode, the footer bar will show the script elements instead of the word and character count, and the document icon in the binder will be yellowish).}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9642 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 When typing dialogue, do }{\f5\fs24\b0\i1 not}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  enter the colon after the character name. Instead, just hit the tab key\hich\f3 \emdash \loch\f3 the colon will be inserted for you. Any names you type at the beginning of dialogue lines will automatically be added to the project auto-complete list (}{\f4\fs20\b1\i0\cf6 <$Scr_Cs::2>Project > Project Settings\loch\af4\hich\af4\dbch\af4\uc1\u8230\'85<!$Scr_Cs::2>}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 ), so that you don\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8217\'92t have to keep typing them out.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9642 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 Characters, Settings and Notes folders have been set up for you, which you can use however you wish\hich\f3 \emdash \loch\f3 or you can delete them and create different folders to organise your project. (These are just regular folders that have had custom icons assigned to them using the }{\f4\fs20\b1\i0\cf6 <$Scr_Cs::2>Documents > Change Icon<!$Scr_Cs::2>}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  feature.)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9642 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 Compile your manuscript for printing by selecting }{\f4\fs20\b1\i0\cf6 <$Scr_Cs::2>File > Compile\loch\af4\hich\af4\dbch\af4\uc1\u8230\'85<!$Scr_Cs::2>}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u9642 	}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0 BBC Radio format expects \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93page turns\u8221\'94 at the end of pages where dialogue is split and spills over to the next page\hich\f3 \emdash \loch\f3 for instance, \u8220\'93(CHARA #1/CONT\u8217\'92D OVER)\u8221\'94. Although a \u8220\'93Page Turns\u8221\'94 element is provided, it will be awkward to add page turns during the drafting stage, even using Scrivener\u8217\'92s page view, so it is recommended that you instead add the page turns either in a word processor after compiling your script, or in Scrivener\u8217\'92s page view only when the script is finished and ready for submission.}
